@article{Tabbaa2014,
abstract = {We investigate cellular response to extracellular signals by using information theory techniques motivated by recent experiments. We present results for the steady state of the following gene regulatory models found in both prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells: a linear transcription-translation model and a positive or negative auto-regulatory model. We calculate both the information capacity and the mutual information exactly for simple models and approximately for the full model. We find that (1) small changes in mutual information can lead to potentially important changes in cellular response and (2) there are diminishing returns in the fidelity of response as the mutual information increases. We calculate the information capacity using Gillespie simulations of a model for the TNF-$\alpha$-NF-$\kappa$ B network and find good agreement with the measured value for an experimental realization of this network. Our results provide a quantitative understanding of the differences in cellular response when comparing experimentally measured mutual information values of different gene regulatory models. Our calculations demonstrate that Gillespie simulations can be used to compute the mutual information of more complex gene regulatory models, providing a potentially useful tool in synthetic biology.},
annote = {I hate this paper!

They stole my priviledge of being the first one to compute the channel capacity of a genetic circuit using the Blahut-Arimoto algorithm...

But anyways, with respect to their science I think is not a super interesting paper. For me their big insight is that under the metric they use to determine if a cell expressed the right amount of a gene or not having less than 1 bit of information is actually useful.

In other words they study the response of cells to different environments (assuming a linear response between signal and gene expression, which I completely disagree) assuming that the cells can only have a binary response. Under this scenario part of the population is exposed to a low signal and it should therefore express a low amount, and the rest of the population is exposed to a high signal, having to express at high levels. Given that gene expression is noisy you'll find cells in the opposite phenotype as they should so the cells would have less than 1 bit of information because they can't even properly distinguish between high and low.

But what these guys find is that even if you have 0.35 bits of information that is "better than nothing" and actually getting the full bit turns out to be very hard having diminishing returns in how much better you do given that you increase your information processing capacity. This last point is analogous to what Bialek showed in his RD curves where you start getting more and more information, but the benefit in fitness is not as by anymore.

Overall I hate this paper because they stoled my glory :-(},
